# AST type guards: prefer `AST.is*` for non-null checks

The Langium-generated type guards (`AST.isViewDeclaration`, `AST.isUseStatement`, etc.) **accept `null` and `undefined`** and return `false` for them. You do not need a separate non-null check before calling them.

## Prefer

```typescript
import { AST } from '@parser'

// One check is enough
if (!AST.isImportableDeclaration(node)) {
  continue
}

// Optional chain result: AST.is* handles undefined
if (AST.isViewDeclaration(node.$container?.$container)) {
  // ...
}
```

## Avoid

```typescript
// Redundant: AST.is*(node) is false when node is null/undefined
if (!node || !AST.isImportableDeclaration(node)) { ... }

// Redundant: same as above
if (viewDecl && AST.isViewDeclaration(viewDecl)) { ... }

// Redundant: AST.isTaoFile(undefined) is false
if (container.$container && AST.isTaoFile(container.$container)) { ... }
```

When you need both “is defined” and “is this AST type”, use **only** the corresponding `AST.is*` call.
